rom Bathtub to Pedestal: An Interview with Oriana Fallaci -- t22 Golda and Her Nemesis: Shulamit Aloni and the Question of Who Is a Jew -- t23 Who Is a Jew? Individual Rights, Jewish Law, the Expediency of Politics, and the “Foreign Woman” -- t24 Golda and the Revival of Feminism -- t25 Nightmare: The Yom Kippur War -- t26 In the Company of Men -- t27 The End -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA feminist biography of the only woman to become prime minister of IsraelIn this authoritative and empathetic biography, Pnina Lahav reexamines the life of Golda Meir (1898–1978) through a feminist lens, focusing on her recurring role as a woman standing alone among men. The Only Woman in the Room is the first book to contend with Meir’s full identity as a woman, Jew, Zionist leader, and one of the founders of Israel, providing a richer portrait of her persona and legacy.Meir, Lahav shows, deftly deflected misogyny as she traveled the path to becoming Israel’s fourth, and only female, prime minister, from 1969 to 1974. Lahav revisits the youthful encounters that forged Meir’s passion for socialist Zionism and reassesses her decision to separate from her husband and leave her children in the care of others. Enduring humiliation and derision from her colleagues, Meir nevertheless led in establishing Israel as a welfare state where social security, workers’ rights, and maternity leave became law. Lahav looks at the challenges that beset Meir’s premiership, particularly the disastrous Yom Kippur War, which led to her resignation and withdrawal from politics, as well as Meir’s bitter duel with feminist and civil rights leader Shulamit Aloni, Meir’s complex relationship with the Israeli and American feminist movements, and the politics that led her to distance herself from feminism altogether.Exploring the tensions between Meir’s personal and political identities, The Only Woman in the Room provides a groundbreaking new account of Meir’s life while also illuminating the difficulties all women face as they try to ascend in male-dominated fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen prime ministerszIsraelvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Presidents & Heads of State.2bisacsh  aA Room of One's Own.  aActivism.  aAll rights reserved.  aAmendment.  aAunt.  aBourgeoisie.  aBuddhism.  aCess.  aClare Boothe Luce.  aComrade.  aDafna.  aDavar.  aDeliberation.  aDisability.  aDisadvantage.  aDissident.  aDouble burden.  aEmptiness.  aEthel Kennedy.  aFemininity.  aFeminism (international relations).  aFeminism.  aFeminist philosophy.  aFeminist theory.  aFirst Lady.  aFlightless bird.  aFurniture.  aGender equality.  aGender neutrality.  aGender role.  aGlass ceiling.  aGolda Meir.  aGroupthink.  aHalakha.  aHanging.  aHenrietta Szold.  aHistadrut.  aHostility.  aHumiliation.  aIn Her Skin.  aInferiority complex.  aInstitution.  aIsolationism.  aIsrael State Archives.  aIsraelis.  aJews.  aJohn Foster Dulles.  aKibbutz.  aKnesset.  aLadies' Home Journal.  aLawlessness.  aLetty Cottin Pogrebin.  aLoneliness.  aMajority rule.  aMajority.  aManicure.  aMapai.  aMemoir.  aMisogyny.  aMother.  aMrs.  aMs.  aMultitude.  aOriana Fallaci.  aPale of Settlement.  aPassword.  aPat Nixon.  aPersephone.  aPrivacy.  aProportionality (mathematics).  aRachel Katznelson-Shazar.  aReason.  aResentment.  aRidicule.  aRitual.  aRuth Bader Ginsburg.  aSecrecy (book).  aSecrecy.  aSecularism.  aSewing.  aSexism.  aShimon Peres.  aSocialist feminism.  aSquat toilet.  aSubconscious.  aSuffragette.  aSuperiority (short story).  